    "created_at": "2011-11-02T04:12:06Z",
    "updated_at": "2011-11-02T04:12:06Z",
    "body": "Rust uses the LLVM `sdiv` and `udiv` instructions for integer division, which have [undefined results](http://llvm.org/docs/LangRef.html#i_udiv) for division by zero.  Using the current Rust compiler built from master on my 32-bit Linux machine, `fn main() { log_err 1/0 }` prints `0` when compiled with optimization.  When compiled without optimization, it yields different results each time it is executed, for example `139268064`.\n\nI'm kind of suprised by both of these results; I'd have expected a hardware exception like the one that jruderman reported.  Does clang do anything different for integer division?  See [this thread](http://lists.cs.uiuc.edu/pipermail/llvmdev/2008-May/014368.html) for some discussion (but no current solutions) from the LLVM point of view.\n",
    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
